<section xml:id="S-11-3-Double-Integrals-General" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"> 
  <title>Double Integrals over General Regions</title>
  
    <objectives>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              How do we define a double integral over a non-rectangular region?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              What general forms do iterated integrals over a non-rectangular region have?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <introduction>
    <p>
      Recall in <xref ref="S-11-1-Double-Integrals-Rectangles">Section</xref> that we defined the double integral of a continuous function <m>f = f(x,y)</m> over a rectangle <m>R = [a,b] \times [c,d]</m> as
      <me>
        \iint_R f(x,y) \, dA = \lim_{m,n \to \infty} \sum_{j=1}^n \sum_{i=1}^m f(x_{ij}^*, y_{ij}^*) \cdot \Delta A.
      </me>
      Furthermore, we have seen that we can evaluate a double integral <m>\iint_R f(x,y) \, dA</m> over <m>R</m> as an iterated integral of either of the forms
      <me>
        \int_a^b \int_c^d f(x,y) \, dy \, dx \quad \quad \text{ or }  \quad \quad \int_c^d \int_a^b f(x,y) \, dx \, dy.
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      It is very rare to have applied or theoretical problems that apply to a rectangular region, so we would like to extend the idea of using iterated integrals to evaluate non-rectangular regions; we explore one such example in the following preview activity.
    </p>

    <exploration xml:id="PA_11_3">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          A tetrahedron is a three-dimensional figure with four faces, each of which is a triangle. A picture of the tetrahedron <m>T</m> with vertices <m>(0,0,0)</m>, <m>(1,0,0)</m>, <m>(0,1,0)</m>, and <m>(0,0,1)</m> is shown at in <xref ref="F_11_3_Tetrahedron_PA">Figure</xref>. If we place one vertex at the origin and let vectors <m>\va</m>, <m>\vb</m>, and <m>\vc</m> be determined by the edges of the tetrahedron that have one end at the origin, then a formula that tells us the volume <m>V</m> of the tetrahedron is
          <men xml:id="eq_11_3_tetrahedron_volume">
            V = \frac{1}{6} \lvert \va \cdot (\vb \times \vc) \rvert.
          </men>
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="F_11_3_Tetrahedron_PA">
          <caption> </caption>
            <interactive title="interactive-F_11_3_Tetrahedron_PA" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
              <slate surface="sage">
                var('t,s,x,y,z')
                from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
                scale=1.5; ao=0.5;aoff=0.25;
                plot1=axes(scale,1,color="black",frame=False,aspect_ratio=1,opacity=ao)+text3d("x",(scale+aoff,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,scale+aoff,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,scale+aoff),fontsize=30)
                f(x,y)=1-x-y
                plot1+=polygon([(1,0,0),(0,1,0),(0,0,0)],color="pink",opacity=0.3,mesh=True)
                plot1+=polygon([(1,0,0),(0,0,1),(0,0,0)],color="pink",opacity=0.3,mesh=True)
                plot1+=polygon([(0,0,1),(0,1,0),(0,0,0)],color="pink",opacity=0.3,mesh=True)
                param(s,t)=(s,t*(1-s),f(s,t*(1-s)))
                #set up grid      n is number of steps in s    m is number of steps in t  
                #a1 is min s    a2 is max s   b1 is min t    b2 is max t
                n=4;m=5;a1=0;a2=1;b1=0;b2=1; 
