      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            State the vectors <m>\va</m>, <m>\vb</m>, and <m>\vc</m> used for our tetrahedron <m>T</m>. Use these vectors in formula <xref ref="eq_11_3_tetrahedron_volume"/> to find the volume of the tetrahedron <m>T</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <me>
              \va = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle, \ \ \ \vb = \langle 0,1,0 \rangle, \ \ \ \text{ and }  \ \ \ \vc = \langle 0,0,1 \rangle,
            </me> and
            <m>V=\frac{1}{6}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Let <m>O=(0,0,0)</m>, <m>P=(1,0,0)</m>,
              <m>Q=(0,1,0)</m>, and <m>R=(0,0,1)</m>.
              With these points as the vertices of the tetrahedron we have
              <me>
                \va = \langle 1,0,0 \rangle, \ \ \ \vb = \langle 0,1,0 \rangle, \ \ \ \text{ and }  \ \ \ \vc = \langle 0,0,1 \rangle,
              </me>.
              Using the formula we obtain
              <md>
                <mrow>\frac{\va \cdot (\vb \times \vc)}{6} \amp = \frac{\vi \cdot (\vj \times \vk)}{6}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \frac{\vi \cdot \vi}{6}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{6}</mrow>
              </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Instead of memorizing or looking up the formula for the volume of a tetrahedron, we can use a double integral to calculate the volume of the tetrahedron <m>T</m>. To see how, notice that the top face of the tetrahedron <m>T</m> is the plane whose equation is
            <me>
              z = 1-(x+y).
            </me>
            We will want to evaluate a pair of iterated integrals on on a non-rectangular region to calculate the volume of the region below this plane and in the first octant region. Reminder: the first octant is the part of <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> that has positive <m>x</m>-, <m>y</m>-, and <m>z</m>-coordinates.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="tetrahedron_base">
            <caption></caption>
              <image width="80%" xml:id="img-tetrahedron_base">
                <sageplot>
                  plot2=polygon([(1,0),(0,1),(0,0),(1,0)],color="pink",axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"],edgecolor="black")
                  plot2+=text("$R$",(0.8,0.1),color="black",fontsize=20,ticks=[[0,1],[0,1]])
                  plot2+=line([(0.3,0),(0.3,0.7)],color="red",zorder=10,thickness=2)+text("$x=a$",(0.375,0.75),fontsize=20,color="red")
                  plot2                
                </sageplot>
              </image>
          </figure>
          <p>  
            The volume of the tetrahedron will be given by double integral 
            <me>\iint_R 1-(x+y) dA</me>
            where the region of integration will the triangle at the base of our tetrahedron (in the <m>xy</m>-plane) as shown in <xref ref="tetrahedron_base"/>. We will need to understand how to express this double integral as an iterated integral using our cross sectional ideas from <xref ref="S-11-2-Iterated-Integrals"/>.
          </p>
          <p>
            We will look at a cross sectional idea along a constant value of <m>x=a</m> which will give an iterated integral of the form
            <me>
              \int_{x=?}^{x=?} \int_{y=?}^{y=?} 1-(x+y) \, dy \, dx.
            </me>
            So, we need to know if we look at <m>R</m> along the trace <m>x=a</m>, what will be the upper and lower bounds on the corresponding <m>y</m> coordinates? 
            <me>\text{If }x=a\text{,then } \underline{\hspace{1.0in}} \leq y \leq \underline{\hspace{1.0in}}</me>
            The lower bound will not depend on the value of <m>a</m> used but the upper bound will, so the expression for the upper bound will be written in terms of <m>a</m>. You should write a couple of sentences to describe how you gave your upper and lower bounds.
          </p> 
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            If we take a cross section of the domain for a fixed value of <m>x</m> as shown in <xref ref="F_11_3_Tetrahedron_PA">Figure</xref>,
            we can see that the <m>y</m> values on the cross section all have a lowest value of 0, but their highest values lie on the line <m>y=1-x</m>.
            We can construct these cross sections for any value of <m>x</m> between 0 and 1, so this triangular region is described by the inequalities
            <m>0 \leq y \leq 1-x</m> and <m>0 \leq x \leq 1</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            If we take a cross section of the domain for a fixed value of <m>x</m> as shown in <xref ref="F_11_3_Tetrahedron_PA">Figure</xref>,
            we can see that the <m>y</m> values on the cross section all have a lowest value of 0, but their highest values lie on the line <m>y=1-x</m>.
            We can construct these cross sections for any value of <m>x</m> between 0 and 1, so this triangular region is described by the inequalities
            <m>0 \leq y \leq 1-x</m> and <m>0 \leq x \leq 1</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain which part of the iterated integral
            <me>
              \int_{x=0}^{x=1} \int_{y=0}^{y=1-x} 1-(x+y) \, dy \, dx
            </me>
            will correspond to the blue cross section in <xref ref="PAcross_section"/>.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="PAcross_section">
            <caption> </caption>
              <interactive title="interactive-PAcross_section" platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
                <slate surface="sage">
                  var('t,s,x,y,z')
                  from sage.plot.plot3d.plot3d import axes
                  scale=1.5; ao=0.5;aoff=0.25;
                  plot3=axes(scale,1,color="black",frame=False,aspect_ratio=1,opacity=ao)+text3d("x",(scale+aoff,0,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("y",(0,scale+aoff,0),fontsize=30)+text3d("z",(0,0,scale+aoff),fontsize=30)
                  f(x,y)=1-x-y
                  plot3+=polygon([(1,0,0),(0,1,0),(0,0,0)],color="pink",opacity=0.3,mesh=True)
                  plot3+=polygon([(1,0,0),(0,0,1),(0,0,0)],color="pink",opacity=0.3,mesh=True)
                  plot3+=polygon([(0,0,1),(0,1,0),(0,0,0)],color="pink",opacity=0.3,mesh=True)
                  param(s,t)=(s,t*(1-s),f(s,t*(1-s)))
                  #set up grid      n is number of steps in s    m is number of steps in t  
                  #a1 is min s    a2 is max s   b1 is min t    b2 is max t
                  n=4;m=5;a1=0;a2=1;b1=0;b2=1; 
                  #c1 is surface color     o1 is surface opacity
                  #c2 and o2 are for constant t value traces
                  #c3 and o3 are for constant s value traces
                  c1="pink"; c2="black"; c3="black"; o1=0.4; o2=0.4; o3=0.4;
                  plot3+=parametric_plot3d(param,(s,a1,a2),(t,b1,b2),color=c1,opacity=o1)
                  for i in range(n+1):
                    sv=a1+i/n*(a2-a1)
                    plot3+=parametric_plot3d(param(sv,t),(t,b1,b2),color=c2,opacity=o2)
                  for i in range(m+1):
                    tv=b1+i/m*(b2-b1)
                    plot3+=parametric_plot3d(param(s,tv),(s,a1,a2),color=c3,opacity=o3)
                  plot3+=parametric_plot3d((0.3,t,f(0.3,t)*s),(t,0,0.7),(s,0,1),color="blue")
                  plot3+=text3d("x=a",(0.35,0.8,0),color="blue",fontsize=20)
                  show(plot3,viewpoint=[[-0.2235,-0.5755,-0.7867],146.02],camera_position=[3.4744,3.7236,2.082])
                </slate>
              </interactive>
          </figure>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            When we slice vertically along <m>x=a</m>, each slice runs from the <m>x</m>-axis to the line <m>y=1-x</m>. The inner integral 
            <me>
               \int_{y=0}^{y=1-x} 1-(x+y) \, dy 
            </me>
            calculates the area of the cross section shown in blue. The limits on <m>y</m> are <m>0 \leq y \leq 1-x</m> for a fixed value of <m>x</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            When we slice vertically along <m>x=a</m>, each slice runs from the <m>x</m>-axis to the line <m>y=1-x</m>. The inner integral 
            <me>
               \int_{y=0}^{y=1-x} 1-(x+y) \, dy 
            </me>
            calculates the area of the cross section shown in blue. The limits on <m>y</m> are <m>0 \leq y \leq 1-x</m> for a fixed value of <m>x</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (twice!) to evaluate the iterated integral
              <me>
                \int_{x=0}^{x=1} \int_{y=0}^{y=1-x} 1-(x+y) \, dy \, dx
              </me>
              and compare to your result from part (a).  (As with iterated integrals over rectangular regions, start with the inner integral.)
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Using basic integration techniques we have
            <md>
              <mrow>\int_{0}^{1} \int_{0}^{1-x} 1-(x+y) \, dy \, dx \amp = \int_0^1 \left(y - xy - \frac{y^2}{2} \right)\mid_0^{1-x} \, dx</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \int_0^1 (1-x) - x(1-x) - \frac{1}{2}(1-x)^2 \, dx</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \int_0^1 x^2-2x+1 \, dx</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x^3}{3} - x^2 + x \right)\mid_0^1</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{6}</mrow>
            </md>.
            This is the same result we obtained from the formula in part (a).
          </p>
        </answer>
