  <subsection>
    <title>Double Integrals over General Regions</title>
    <p>
      So far, we have learned that a double integral over a rectangular region may be interpreted in one of three ways:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\iint_R f(x,y) \, dA</m> tells us the volume of the solid bounded by the graph of <m>f</m> above and the <m>xy</m>-plane below and over the rectangle <m>R</m> minus the volume of the solids the graph of <m>f</m> bounds below the <m>xy</m>-plane under the rectangle <m>R</m>;
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\frac{1}{A(R)} \iint_R f(x,y) \, dA</m>, where <m>A(R)</m> is the area of <m>R</m> tells us the average value of the function <m>f</m> on <m>R</m>. If <m>f(x, y) \geq  0</m> on <m>R</m>, we can interpret this average value of <m>f</m> on <m>R</m> as the height of the box with base <m>R</m> that has the same volume as the volume of the surface defined by <m>f</m> over <m>R</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If <m>f(x,y)</m> measure the density (in amount per unit area) of a material in the region <m>R</m>, then <m>\iint_R f(x,y) \, dA</m> will give the total amount of material in <m>R</m>. 
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      As we saw in <xref ref="PA_11_1">Preview Activity</xref>, a function <m>f = f(x,y)</m> may be considered over regions other than rectangular ones, and thus we want to understand how to set up double integrals as iterated integrals over non-rectangular regions. Note that if we can, then the three interpretations of the double integral noted above will naturally extend to solid regions with non-rectangular bases.
    </p>

   <!--  <p>
      So, suppose <m>f</m> is a continuous function on a closed, bounded domain <m>D</m>. For example, consider <m>D</m> as the circular domain shown at left in <xref ref="F_11_3_nonrect_domain_1">Figure</xref>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="F_11_3_nonrect_domain_1">
      <caption>Left: A non-rectangular domain. Right: Enclosing this domain in a rectangle.</caption>
      <sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
        <image source="images/fig_11_3_circular"/>
        <image source="images/fig_11_3_circular_rect"/>
        </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>
      We can enclose <m>D</m> in a rectangular domain <m>R</m> as shown at right in <xref ref="F_11_3_nonrect_domain_1">Figure</xref> and extend the function <m>f</m> to be defined over <m>R</m> in order to be able to use the definition of the double integral over a rectangle. We extend <m>f</m> in such a way that its values at the points in <m>R</m> that are not in <m>D</m> contribute 0 to the value of the integral. In other words, define a function <m>F = F(x, y)</m> on <m>R</m> as
      <me>
        F(x,y) = \begin{cases}f(x,y), \amp \text{ if }  (x,y) \in D, \\ 0, \amp \text{ if }  (x,y) \not\in D
        \end{cases} .
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      We then say that the double integral of <m>f</m> over <m>D</m><idx><h>double integral over a general region</h></idx> is the same as the double integral of <m>F</m> over <m>R</m>, and thus
      <me>
        \iint_D f(x,y) \, dA = \iint_R F(x,y) \, dA.
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      In practice, we just ignore everything that is in <m>R</m> but not in <m>D</m>, since these regions contribute 0 to the value of the integral.
    </p> -->
    <p>
      The key idea to writing double integrals as iterated integrals (as shown in <xref ref="S-11-2-Iterated-Integrals"/> and <xref ref="PA_11_3"/>) is to slice the region of integration along a trace (with one of the coordinates held constant) and express the range of the other coordinate in terms of an inequality. In <xref ref="PA_11_3"/>, we saw how the region given in <xref ref="tetrahedron_base"/> can be described by the inequalities <m>0 \leq x \leq 1</m> and <m>0 \leq y \leq 1-x</m>. Notice how for different values of <m>x</m> there is a different range of values for <m>y</m>, which means our region is NOT rectangular. Compare this to the rectangular regions of integration from <xref ref="S-11-2-Iterated-Integrals"/> which were all of the form <m>a \leq x \leq b</m> and <m>c \leq y \leq d</m> (with <m>a,b,c,d</m> constants).
    </p>
    <p>
      Both of these forms for the inequalities leads to a nice way to write the corresponding double integral as an iterated integral by considering the inner integral to evaluate the cross section area while the outer integral sums up the corresponding cross section volumes as the width of the slices goes to zero (demonstrated in  <xref ref="F_11_2_Cross_section_y_slab_sum"/>).
    </p>
    <p>
      What kind of 2D regions can we express using this slicing/inequality idea? The key here is that we need the same upper and lower bound expressions for each slice.
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="prop-verticallysimple">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A region is called vertically simple if it can be described by a set of inequalities of the form
          <md>
            <mrow> a \leq x \leq b</mrow>
            <mrow> g_1(x) \leq  y \leq g_2(x)</mrow>
          </md>
          which corresponds geometrically to the region in <xref ref="vertsimple"/>
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="vertsimple">
          <caption></caption>
          <image width="60%" xml:id="img-vertsimple">
            <sageplot>
              var('x,y,t,s')
              f(x)=(x-2)^2/5+0.5-0.25*sin(4*x); g(x)= 0.25*cos(7*x)+0.2*x+1.5;
              a=0.5; b=1.5; dx=b-a; n=25;
              bottom=[(a+i*dx/n,f(a+i*dx/n)) for i in range(n+1)]
              top=[(b-i*dx/n,g(b-i*dx/n)) for i in range(n+1)]
              points=bottom+top
              plot4=polygon(points,color="pink",edgecolor="black",xmin=0,xmax=1.75,ymin=0,ymax=2,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"])
              m=6;xv=[0.5+i/m for i in range(1,m)]
              for xval in xv:
                plot4+=line([(xval,f(xval)),(xval,g(xval))],color="orange",thickness=2,linestyle="--")
              plot4+=plot(f(x),(x,a,b),color="red",thickness=3,ticks=[[a,b],[]],tick_formatter=[["$x=a$","$x=b$"],[]],fontsize=15)
              plot4+=plot(g(x),(x,a,b),color="blue",thickness=3)
              plot4+=line([(a,g(a)),(a,0)],color="gray",thickness=1)+line([(b,g(b)),(b,0)],color="gray",thickness=1)
              plot4+=text("$g_1(x)$",(1,0.7),color="red",fontsize=20)+text("$g_2(x)$",(1,2.1),color="blue",fontsize=20)
              plot4  
            </sageplot>
          </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
          A region is called vertically simple if it can be described by a set of inequalities of the form
          <md>
            <mrow> c \leq y \leq d</mrow>
            <mrow> h_1(y) \leq  x \leq h_2(y)</mrow>
          </md>
          which corresponds geometrically to the region in <xref ref="horzsimple"/>
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="horzsimple">
          <caption></caption>
          <image width="60%" xml:id="img-horzsimple">
            <sageplot>
              var('x,y,t,s')
              f(x)=(x-1.5)^2/4+0.5-0.15*sin(5*x); g(x)= 0.25*cos(3*x)+0.2*x+1.5;
              a=0.5; b=1.5; dx=b-a; n=25;
              bottom=[(f(a+i*dx/n),a+i*dx/n) for i in range(n+1)]
              top=[(g(b-i*dx/n),b-i*dx/n) for i in range(n+1)]
              points=bottom+top
              plot5=polygon(points,color="pink",edgecolor="black",xmin=0,xmax=2,ymin=0,ymax=2,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"])
              m=6;xv=[0.5+i/m for i in range(1,m)]
              for xval in xv:
                plot5+=line([(f(xval),xval),(g(xval),xval)],color="orange",thickness=2,linestyle="--")
              plot5+=parametric_plot((f(x),x),(x,a,b),color="red",thickness=3,ticks=[[],[a,b]],tick_formatter=[[],["$y=c$","$y=d$"]],fontsize=15)
              plot5+=parametric_plot((g(x),x),(x,a,b),color="blue",thickness=3)
              plot5+=line([(g(a),a),(0,a)],color="gray",thickness=1)+line([(g(b),b),(0,b)],color="gray",thickness=1)
              plot5+=text("$x=h_1(y)$",(0.5,1.6),color="red",fontsize=20)+text("$x=h_2(y)$",(1.5,1.6),color="blue",fontsize=20)
              plot5 
            </sageplot>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <p>
      A vertically simple region is one that can be split into vertical slices (of the form <m>x=constant</m> for <m>x</m> in the range <m>[a,b]</m>) where every vertical slice has the same upper and lower bound( <m>g_1(x) \leq y \leq g_2(x)</m>). A horizontally simple region is one that can be split into horizontal slices (of the form <m>y=constant</m> for <m>x</m> in the range <m>[c,d]</m>) where every horizontal slice has the same upper and lower bound (<m>h_1(x) \leq y \leq h_2(x)</m>).
    </p>
    <example>
      <introduction>
        <p>
        Let <m>D</m> be the triangular region in the <m>xy</m>-plane with vertices <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>(2,0)</m>, and <m>(2,3)</m>, shown in <xref ref="triang-region"/>. We want to decide if <m>D</m> is horizontally simple, then we will consider if <m>D</m> is vertically simple. For simplicity, we will refer to the three sides as the horizontal side (from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(2,0)</m>), the vertical side (from <m>(2,0)</m> to <m>(2,3)</m>), and the diagonal side (from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(2,3)</m>).
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="triang-region">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="80%" xml:id="img-triang-region">
          <sageplot>
            plot6=polygon([(0,0),(2,0),(2,3)],color="lightblue",edgecolor="black",gridlines=True,xmin=0,xmax=3,ymin=0,ymax=3,zorder=5)
            plot6+=text("$D$",(1.8,2.2),color="black",fontsize=20,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"],zorder=6)
            plot6                
          </sageplot>
        </image>
      </figure>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <p>
          Remember that a vertical line will correspond algebraically to <m>x=constant</m>. We want to know if every vertical slice in the region <m>D</m> will have the same upper and lower bounds (which may depend on the value of <m>x</m>). Several vertical slices in the region <m>D</m> are shown in <xref ref="vertsimple-tri"/> where you can see that the lower bound (of the <m>y</m>-variable) for every vertical slice is given by <m>y=0</m>. The upper bound (of the <m>y</m>-variable) for every vertical slice is given by <m>y=\frac{3}{2} x</m>. Algebraically, if you take any constant value, <m>k</m>, in the interval <m>[0,2]</m>, then the following statement describes the vertical strips of the region <m>D</m>:
          <me>\text{Along }x=k\text{ the }y\text{-coordinates will go from }0\text{ to }\frac{3}{2}x</me>
          which corresponds to the inequalities 
          <me> 0\leq x \leq 2 \quad \quad 0 \leq y \leq \frac{3}{2} x</me>
          as a descriptions for <m>D</m>. Thus, the region <m>D</m> is vertically simple.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="vertsimple-tri">
          <caption></caption>
          <image width="60%" xml:id="img-vertsimple-tri">
            <sageplot>
              plot7=polygon([(0,0),(2,0),(2,3)],color="lightblue",edgecolor="black",gridlines=True,xmin=0,xmax=3,ymin=0,ymax=3,zorder=5,ticks=[[0,1,2,3],[0,1,2,3]])
              plot7+=text("$D$",(1.8,2.2),color="black",fontsize=20,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"],zorder=6)
              vals=[2/5,4/5,6/5,8/5]
              for v in vals:
                plot7+=line([(v,1.5*v),(v,0)],color="magenta",thickness=2,zorder=7,linestyle="--")
              plot7+=line([(0,0),(3,0)],color="red",thickness=2,zorder=8)+text("$y=0$",(2.5,.25),color="red",fontsize=15)
              plot7+=line([(0,0),(4,6)],color="blue",thickness=2,zorder=8)+text("$y=\\frac{3}{2}x$",(1.5,2.75),color="blue",fontsize=15)
              plot7      
            </sageplot>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Remember that a horizontal line will correspond algebraically to <m>y=constant</m>. We want to know if every horizontal slice in the region <m>D</m> will have the same upper and lower bounds (which may depend on the value of <m>y</m>). Several horizontal slices in the region <m>D</m> are shown in <xref ref="horzsimple-tri"/> where you can see that the lower bound (of the <m>x</m>-variable) for every horizontal slice is given by <m>x=\frac{2}{3} y</m>. The upper bound (of the <m>x</m>-variable) for every horizontal slice is given by <m>x=2</m>. Algebraically, if you take any constant value, <m>k</m>, in the interval <m>[0,3]</m>, then the following statement describes the horizontal strips of the region <m>D</m>:
            <me>\text{Along }y=k\text{ the }x\text{-coordinates will go from }\frac{2}{3} x\text{ to }2</me>
            which corresponds to the inequalities 
            <me> 0\leq y \leq 3 \quad \quad \frac{2}{3} \leq y \leq 2 x</me>
            as a descriptions for <m>D</m>. Thus, the region <m>D</m> is horizontally simple.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="horzsimple-tri">
            <caption></caption>
            <image width="60%" xml:id="img-horzsimple-tri">
              <sageplot>
                plot7=polygon([(0,0),(2,0),(2,3)],color="lightblue",edgecolor="black",gridlines=True,xmin=0,xmax=3,ymin=0,ymax=3,zorder=5,ticks=[[0,1,2,3],[0,1,2,3]])
                plot7+=text("$D$",(1.8,2.2),color="black",fontsize=20,axes_labels=["$x$","$y$"],zorder=6)
                vals=[2/3,4/3,6/3,8/3]
                for v in vals:
                  plot7+=line([(2/3*v,v),(2,v)],color="magenta",thickness=2,zorder=7,linestyle="--")
                plot7+=line([(0,0),(4,6)],color="red",thickness=2,zorder=8)+text("$x=\\frac{2}{3} y$",(1.5,2.75),color="red",fontsize=15)
                plot7+=line([(2,0),(2,4)],color="blue",thickness=2,zorder=8)+text("$x=2$",(2.25,1.5),color="blue",fontsize=15)
                plot7                
              </sageplot>
            </image>
          </figure>
          <p>
            This example shows that just because a region is vertically simple does not mean that it is <em>not</em> horizontally simple as well. In general, a 2D region is 
            <ul>
              <li>horizontally simple (but not vertically simple) </li>
              <li>vertically simple (but not horizontally simple) </li>
              <li>both horizontally simple and vertically simple </li>
              <li>neither horizontally simple or vertically simple  </li>
            </ul>
            and as you will see later, you may want to switch the description of your region to make the algebra of evaluating an integral easier.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </example>
    <example>
      <p>
        example that is NOT simple in either direction, then describe how to break into regions that are horizontally simple or vertically simple.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id=" ">
